article.headline: LSU 67, Tulane 48
article.story: BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- LSU coach John Brady is still searching for consistency on offense, but he need not worry about his Tigers on the defensive end. LSU held Tulane to 34.4 percent shooting and went on a 17-0 run over the final 8:09 of the first half as the Tigers eased their way to a 67-48 win over the Green Wave on Tuesday night. "This was a really good win for our team, and we defended Tulane pretty well," Brady said. "We've put together three pretty good games on the defensive end, which is good for us to do." The Tigers (7-0) have limited their last four opponents to under 37 percent shooting. Jaime Lloreda posted his fourth double-double of the year, scoring 22 points and pulling down 10 rebounds. Darrel Mitchell, in his first start of the year, tied his career high with 19 points, including four 3-pointers, while Tack Minor came off the bench and also tied his season high with 12. "I think Tack Minor had his best game in an LSU uniform so far," Brady said. "Darrel again made some timely shots, and I have all the confidence in the world in him." Tulane (5-3) was plagued by poor shooting and was just 1-of-11 in free throw attempts. "It's absurd to shoot nine percent from the free throw line," Tulane coach Shawn Finney said. "That may be a little fatigue, but we've got to get up and make free throws." Wayne Tinsley led the Green Wave with 12 points while Vytas Tatarunas added 10. LSU scored 25 points off of 17 Tulane turnovers. "We had good looks, we had the ball at the basket, but you have to finish," Finney said. "We got the ball down low and tried to draw a foul or score, but we couldn't finish."
